Student Scores¶

Description of Dataset¶

This dataset is of student achievement in secondary education of two Portuguese schools. The dataset is available on kaggle from this link. The data is originally from Paulo Cortez, University of Minho, and available on this link. </br>

The data includes demographic information about students (such as gender, age, and adress), social information (such as number of family members, parents status, together or apart, romantic relationship of student, in a relationship or not) as well as some information about personal habits (such as how much free time do they have, how much time do they study, and how frequently do they go out), and most importantly academic information about the students, the academic information comprises of the grades in the Portuguese language over three academic periods, and one other feature; the number of absence days of students over the period of the study. </br>

The features mentioned were collected by using school reports and questionnaires. The data is intended to be used in machine learning appluications to predict the grade of the third period given knowledge of the rest of the demographic, social, and personal features in the data, as well as the grades of the students in the first two periods. </br>

I found this dataset very interesting to investigate as we can not only use it in its intended context, but we also can learn more about different non-academic factors which might affect students performance so we can ultimately suggest how we can enhance students well being and performance. </br>

All features in the dataset:

Some notes on the features¶

  1. I hope you excuse my pun Variable Taxonomy. :"D There are different ways to classify different variables we have come across in this course, so cascading them one after another feels pretty much like.. taxonomy.
  2. Although, generally speaking, the age is a continous variable, I here treat as a discrete variable because only integer value ages are recorded. And hence it will make more sense to treat it as such for the porpuse of our visualizations.
  3. While letter grades might be considered ordinal variables, I find the numeric grades in this context better dealt with as quantiative features, not just for the obvious reason that they are numeric values and that they can be meaninfully added and have a meaningful zero point, but also because the values are too many to be considered categorical.
  4. I found variable names are handy and easy to remember, hence I won't change any. </br>

The main features of interest in the dataset¶

I'm most interested in finding out if theres is any relation between the grades and one, or a collection of of the features present in the dataset.

My expectations for what features of the dataset will help support my investigation into the features of interest¶

Firstly, I expect that absences will have a great impact on students performance, maybe at least for students who don't take extra paid classes. Otherwise we can make the conclusion that the educational system implented in the schools where the data is collected is not effective at all.</br>

Secondly, I expect a combination of social factors to play a role in determinging the students' performance, some the features concerning family size, emotional environment of the student (represented by romantic relationship and family status, I will consider them to be an indicator for the emotional environment), and their educational level.</br>

Finally, I think some of personal factors play an important role as well, whether the students want to persue higher education, free time, study time, and frequency of going out.

Final Notes on The Dataset¶

There are 649 students in the dataset with 32 features, after removing failures. Most variables are categorical and the ordinal ones have been declared so to facilitate exploration. But the most important variables G1, G2, and G3 are numeric and so are age and absences.

Univariate Exploration¶

Now that we have performed some wrangling and cleaning on the dataset, and made sure tha the data is ready for exploratory analysis, it's time to begin this process by univariate feature exploration. As most of the variables in this dataset are categorical data, it won't be very interesting to explore each of them alone. As most of them will be presented in bar charts which show the category destibutions, which is very important and essential to understand the dataset, reach sound conclusions, and dig out any insights from it, but just not as interesting as the other parts of data exploration will be. </br>

Grades, asa numeric variables will be most appropriatly viewed using a violin plot,rather than a histogram or a box plot as their ranges are relatively small. This applies to absences as well (the source states they range from 0 to 93). And finally age can be viewed using a histogram of very small bin size.</br>

because most of the variables are categorical it more convenient and effecient to create a function to draw them and loop over all categorical variables.

In [14]:
def bar_chart_with_perc_of(var_name, ax = None):
    """"" 
    Draw bar chart(s) for categorical variables.
    var_name: the name of the variable in the students dataset.
    ax: (optional) if more than one variable is to be plotted pass the plt.axes corresponding to each
    variable.
    """""
            
    # prepare variable to print percentages atop bars
    var_counts = students[var_name].value_counts().sort_index()
    var_levels = var_counts.index
    # with axes
    if ax: 
        sb.countplot(data = students, x = var_name, color = base_color, ax = ax, order = var_levels)
    # without axes
    else:
        sb.countplot(data = students, x = var_name, color = base_color, order = var_levels)

        
    # put percentages on top of bars
    for i,n in enumerate(var_counts):
        per = np.round(n / n_students * 100, 2)
        txt = '{}%'.format(per)
        if ax:
            ax.text(i, n, txt, ha = 'center', va = 'bottom')
        else: 
           plt.text(i, n, txt, fontsize = 16-len(students[var_name].unique()), ha = 'center', va = 'bottom')

Bivariate Exploration¶

I start by examining potential correlation between numerical varaibles. Both using a heat map and using a scatter grid. As a scatter grid can give us more informatino and understanding of data distribution but the correlation coeffecients are more suitable as predictors of the existance of any relations.

In [26]:
sct_plt = sb.PairGrid(data = students, vars = numeric_vars)
sct_plt = sct_plt.map_diag(plt.hist, bins = 20);
sct_plt.map_offdiag(plt.scatter);

The only strong correlations we can see in these scatter plots are between the interest features themselves; the grades of different periods. This makes sense as the performance of a student is not expected to change drastically from one period to another. I was expecting a stronger correlation between absences and grades, as I thought the number of absence days would be an indicator of perfomance. But it did not show that much of effect. </br> We will further investigate correlation cooffecients to make sure of our findings.

The results of these box plots are very interesting! Now we start to see some trends in our data. And we start to learn what features of the data affect the grades. For example we see clearly from the box plot of travel time that systematically, the less time a student needs to travel to his or her school the better on average that they perfrom. We also see that there is a strong effect of the students desire to continue or not to persue higher education and their academic performance.

More interesingly we can see that some social metrics have a considerable effect on students performance. For example we see that the higher the education level of the students' parents is the more likely they are to do well at school. And we see that the children of teachers do better than children of parents in other professions.

And from the personal habits factors, we can see that the students who go out moderately (class 2, the next to lowest class) have on average better performance than other students who go out either too little or too much.

Summary of observations¶

From the graphs present above in our bivariate exploration I would like to provide the following notes refelcting on the results in view of my earlier expectations.

I will start first by stating all the features which show some effect (when I say shows some effect this means that the median, and the five number summaries of each level of this variable eaither increase or decrease systematically in as we move in one direction, in the case of ordinal variables, or from level to the other, in the case of nominal varaibels.)

These Variables are:

  1. School: there is a significant difference between the scores of students from the two schools.
  2. Sex: Female students have higher scores distribution than male students.
  3. Address: Students in one location have lower score distribution than the other. (this might be because of travel time)
  4. Mother Education: The higher the mother's educaitonal level the higher the scores.
  5. Father Education: The higher the father's educaitonal level the higher the scores.
  6. Mother Job: Children of teacher have significantly higher grades than the rest of the students.
  7. Father Job: Children of teacher have significantly higher grades than the rest of the students.
  8. Travel Time: The longer the travel time the lower the score distribution.
  9. Study Time: The higher the study time the higher the score distribution (very expectedly so :"D). Yet the last two levels of study time don't have much differences.
  10. Activities: Students who participate in activities have on average higher grades.
  11. Higher Education: Students who want to pursue higher education have on average much higher grades.
  12. Internet: Students with internet access have on average higher grades.
  13. Family Relations: Students with better family relations have better grades.
  14. Go Out: Students who are in the second level, next to least, have the highest grades. And from there, there is a systematic decrease in grades when going out is more frequent.
  15. Daiy Alchohol use: The higher the consumption the lower the grades.

If we are to make a machine learning model, I would recommend that these variable be assigned higher weights in prediction or be the only ones to be used. But for the porpuses of our analysis, finding the factors which can effect the students performance, we have different considerations and not all factors can be treated as useful.

Firstly, there are the factors which only present can not, with only the information available to us in this study, be generalized to give any conclusions about education quality in general. These variables are:

  1. School.
  2. Address.
  3. Sex.

The first two are not useful for our study at all, maybe they only reflect school quality, neighborhood quality, to make sure of that we need further information. But they cannot generalize to a useful conclusion about educational systems. Unless The school with the higher grades distribution has a systematic difference in their educational systems. Which in turn suggest adapting their version of an educational system.

The third of the three, the gender of the students, might suggest that girls are better at learning languages than boys. So that boys might need more attention in such subjects.

Secondly there are social factors which affect the students grades, these can be presented to parents and schools in order to utilize them to encourage certain traits from parents or family in general. Those are:

  1. Mother And Father Education.
  2. Mother And Father Jobs.
  3. Family Relations.

Better family relations enhance students' performance. And the higher the educational level of the parents the better the kids perform. The last observation can be taken into consideration and students of parents with lower education levels be given more attention for example. Lastly we could ask teachers what they do more with their children and see if education systems can be adapted to provide similar care or attention, as it is shown that it is associated with higher grade distributions.

The rest of the factors can be reasonably be in the control of the students. And hence we can present them to the students as suggestions to make them more likely to be able to het higher grades. Also they can be presented to parents and people in autherity as well, I will give a rationale for this shortly. These variables are:

  1. Travel Time.
  2. Study Time.
  3. Activities
  4. Higher Education
  5. Go Out.
  6. Daily Alchohol Use.

The messages which we can give to students from studying this dataset (although it is not statistically verified to be signifcant, which we need to do, but this is the scope of our study for now) -- the messages are:

  1. Study more. Very obviously :"D if you study more you are gonna get better results.
  2. Go to a school neer your home. The higher the travel time the less your performance is expected to be.
  3. Aim high. Having a goal for your study will likely affect your performance positively.
  4. Balance you time between studying and going out and doing other activities. This point is very interesting for investigation in the multivariate section, in order to learn what combinations are best.
  5. Limit your use of alchohol on week days. Students who use alchohol more on week days perform more poorly.

These findings are going to guide our invistigation in the next section. Especially that we did not find strong correlations between numeric variables so the multivariate exploration we need to do is regarding the categorical variables.

And although the results from earlier bivariate explorations are quite promising, I would like to make sure that these results can not be clearer if we perform some axis transformation. And as I suspect it likely that some effects can double the grades or multiply them by a factor close to 2 (I don't have a solid justification by 2 seems quite good for the task as it is the smallest integer that can be a base for a log as well).

Therefore, I will explore next the same plots with the average grades but this time on a transformed log sale.

In [30]:
# compute the logarithm of price to make multivariate plotting easier
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """ quick function for computing log and power operations """
    if not inverse:
        return np.log2(x)
    else:
        return np.power(2, x)

Multivariate Exploration¶

As we have seen from the bivariate exploration that the numerical features do not have almost any correlation with the target features, I will restrict my investigation in this section to multivariate exploration of pairs of categorical variables with the target features. And I will try to systematically go through them in order to extract as much information as we can from this dataset in our topic.

I will focus on the variables which we found from the previous section have the most effect on the target features; the grades.

def grades_with(x_prop, c_prop):
    """
    Draw a pointplot of two properties with grades.

    c_prop: variable name from students for color.
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = [12, 4])

                       palette = 'Blues', linestyles = '', dodge = 0.4)

All the features chosen in this stage show expected results. And they also make very good material for the presentation.

The most interesting highlight I see in this data is that when each of the following features interacts with studytime it reinfornces the previous conlcusions. So on conclusion we might say:

  1. The activities and goout variables shows that student who have other Extracuricular activities, or just go out more perform better than those who don't go out at all or do any activities. The data also shows that too much of those can harm your grades. So students who do activities and study lightly do better than those who don't do activities and study lightly. But when they both study hard the ones who do not have activities do better. So is the case with going out, there is a critical point after which the more you go out the worse you do on your studies.
  2. traveltime shows that the time spend commuting daily affects students grades negatively. The higher the travel time the less a student's performance is expected to be.
  3. Dalc and Walc suggest that the more alchohol you consume in general the worse you perform. But this is true especially during week days.
  4. higher shows that students who have higher goals do better than those who don't have goals they want to achieve, even when they study for the same number of hours.
